---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="The Invisible Dashboard" section={10}>
  <SectionHeader n={10} title="The Invisible Dashboard" meta="~500w · interactive" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      Consider what it feels like to drive a well-engineered car. You are not reading
      the instrument cluster. You are driving. The speedometer exists at the edge of
      your vision, but you are not looking at it. You know you are doing approximately
      ninety kilometres per hour the way you know roughly where your hands are — through
      a kind of ambient proprioception, not conscious measurement.
    </p>

    <p>
      The instrument cluster intrudes only when something is wrong. The temperature
      gauge drifts toward red. The fuel light appears. The engine warning illuminates.
      These are not subtle. They are designed to be impossible to ignore. But that is
      the entire design contract: invisible when normal, unmissable when not.
    </p>

    <p>
      A glass cockpit in a commercial aircraft operates the same way. In stable cruise,
      the displays are calm — the information is present but it does not demand attention.
      In an abnormal situation, the flight deck changes state. Warnings sound. Displays
      change colour and priority. The information hierarchy shifts entirely to surface
      what matters right now.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>The data disappears and what remains is awareness. So well tuned to one signal
      that it becomes ambient. That's the goal. Build for a feeling, not a layout.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      Neither the car's instrument cluster nor the glass cockpit feels like a dashboard
      in the BI sense. They feel like knowing. The interface has been so carefully tuned
      to the relevant signal that the interface itself disappears. What remains is
      not information — it is a state of the world, directly perceived.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the goal. Not a better layout. Not a smarter chart. Not a more flexible
      query interface. A dashboard so well calibrated to one question — the question
      that actually matters to the person using it — that the dashboard becomes ambient.
      You open it and you know. You do not read it. You do not scan it. You know.
    </p>

    <p>
      Getting there requires everything this book has argued for. <a href={`${base}section/3`}>The one question test</a>,
      so you know which signal matters. <a href={`${base}section/2`}>The signal design work</a>, so the number has
      a threshold and a context. <a href={`${base}section/4`}>The audience definition</a>, so the question is the right
      one for the right person. <a href={`${base}section/5`}>The empty state design</a>, so normal is visually quiet
      and abnormal is visually loud. It requires saying no to the second panel,
      and the third, and the donut chart, and the table, and the filter that someone
      requested because they like to drill down.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="The discipline">
      The invisible dashboard is not a product of minimalism as aesthetic.
      It is a product of discipline — of having answered the hard questions about
      what actually matters and having the conviction to build for that and nothing else.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      The interactive below is an attempt to render this literally. One number.
      One colour. One meaning. The colour shifts — warm and quiet when the business
      metric is nominal, cooling and sharpening as it moves toward a threshold,
      demanding attention when it crosses one. No panel chrome. No axes. No legend.
      You just know.
    </p>

    <p>
      It is, deliberately, almost nothing. That is the point.
    </p>

  </div>

  <!-- Interactive: The Invisible Dashboard -->
  <div class="inv-wrapper">
    <div class="inv-chrome">The Invisible Dashboard — ambient indicator</div>
    <div class="inv-body">
      <div class="inv-orb-container">
        <div class="inv-orb" id="inv-orb"></div>
        <div class="inv-reading" id="inv-reading">—</div>
        <div class="inv-label" id="inv-label">Monthly churn</div>
      </div>
      <div class="inv-state-label" id="inv-state-label">Loading…</div>
      <div class="inv-controls">
        <span class="inv-ctrl-label">Simulate</span>
        <button class="inv-ctrl-btn" data-value="1.8" title="All good">All good</button>
        <button class="inv-ctrl-btn" data-value="2.6" title="Watch closely">Elevated</button>
        <button class="inv-ctrl-btn inv-ctrl-btn--alert" data-value="3.4" title="Act now">Alert</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      Three states. One signal. No noise. Every decision about what to include
      in this instrument was made by removing something that did not add meaning.
      The number is present because it anchors the feeling in something concrete.
      The colour carries the urgency. Everything else was removed.
    </p>

    <p>
      The goal is not to build this exact instrument. The goal is to build with
      this level of discipline — to know which one signal matters enough to hold
      the entire screen, and to trust that knowing it is enough.
    </p>

    <p style="margin-top: 2em; color: var(--ink-300); font-style: italic; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
      — End of The Invisible Dashboard.
      <a href="https://heluvaguy.github.io/invisible-interface/" style="color: var(--terra-400); text-decoration: none; margin-left: 0.4em;">
        Book I: The Invisible Interface →
      </a>
    </p>
  </div>

</Base>

<style>
  .inv-wrapper {
    margin: var(--sp-8) 0;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px dashed var(--ink-100);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
  }

  .inv-chrome {
    background: var(--paper-1);
    border-bottom: var(--border-subtle);
    padding: var(--sp-2) var(--sp-4);
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    color: var(--ink-300);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    font-weight: 500;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .inv-body {
    padding: var(--sp-12) var(--sp-6);
    background: var(--paper-0);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--sp-6);
    min-height: 240px;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  .inv-orb-container {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--sp-3);
  }

  .inv-orb {
    width: 80px;
    height: 80px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    transition: background var(--dur-crawl) var(--ease-soft),
                box-shadow var(--dur-crawl) var(--ease-soft);
    background: var(--paper-2);
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 0 transparent;
  }

  .inv-orb.state-ok {
    background: var(--terra-100);
    box-shadow: 0 0 32px 4px rgba(201, 149, 106, 0.18);
  }

  .inv-orb.state-warn {
    background: #d4a055;
    box-shadow: 0 0 40px 8px rgba(212, 160, 85, 0.25);
  }

  .inv-orb.state-alert {
    background: var(--cold-pulse);
    box-shadow: 0 0 48px 12px rgba(231, 76, 60, 0.28);
  }

  .inv-reading {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 40px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--ink-900);
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1;
    transition: color var(--dur-crawl) var(--ease-soft);
  }

  .inv-reading.state-alert {
    color: var(--cold-pulse);
  }

  .inv-label {
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    color: var(--ink-300);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .inv-state-label {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-300);
    font-style: italic;
    transition: color var(--dur-crawl) var(--ease-soft);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .inv-state-label.state-alert {
    color: var(--cold-pulse);
    font-style: normal;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .inv-controls {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--sp-2);
    border-top: var(--border-subtle);
    padding-top: var(--sp-4);
    width: 100%;
    justify-content: center;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .inv-ctrl-label {
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    color: var(--ink-100);
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    margin-right: var(--sp-1);
  }

  .inv-ctrl-btn {
    background: var(--paper-1);
    border: 0.5px solid var(--paper-3);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    padding: var(--sp-1) var(--sp-3);
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    color: var(--ink-500);
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: background var(--dur-fast), border-color var(--dur-fast), color var(--dur-fast);
  }

  .inv-ctrl-btn:hover {
    background: var(--paper-2);
    color: var(--ink-700);
  }

  .inv-ctrl-btn--alert {
    border-color: #f5c6c6;
    color: #c0392b;
  }

  .inv-ctrl-btn--alert:hover {
    background: #fff0f0;
  }
</style>

<script>
  const orb = document.getElementById('inv-orb') as HTMLDivElement;
  const reading = document.getElementById('inv-reading') as HTMLDivElement;
  const stateLabel = document.getElementById('inv-state-label') as HTMLDivElement;

  function setState(value: number) {
    const display = value.toFixed(1) + '%';
    reading.textContent = display;

    orb.className = 'inv-orb';
    reading.className = 'inv-reading';
    stateLabel.className = 'inv-state-label';

    if (value < 2.5) {
      orb.classList.add('state-ok');
      stateLabel.textContent = 'Within normal range — nothing requires attention';
    } else if (value < 3.0) {
      orb.classList.add('state-warn');
      stateLabel.textContent = 'Elevated — worth watching, not yet a problem';
    } else {
      orb.classList.add('state-alert');
      reading.classList.add('state-alert');
      stateLabel.classList.add('state-alert');
      stateLabel.textContent = 'Above threshold — consider running the retention campaign';
    }
  }

  document.querySelectorAll('.inv-ctrl-btn').forEach(btn => {
    btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const val = parseFloat((btn as HTMLElement).dataset.value!);
      setState(val);
    });
  });

  // Start in nominal state
  setState(1.8);
</script>
